pciszek@nyx10.cs.du.edu (Paul Ciszek) writes:

>Given that k = 1.381x10^-16 erg/K, and the ambient temperature of the
>universe is 3.2K, an "ideal computer" running at 3.2K would consume at
>least 4.4x10^-16 erg every time it set or cleared a bit.  (To run a
>computer any colder than the cosmic background, we would have to expend
>extra energy to run a heat pump.)

Hehe, I wonder how they arrived at this number. Have you taken into
consideration that neutrinos are not necessarily massless?

In general, I get the feeling that the calculations look rather
unbelievable.


